column132: A fully electronic notebook is missing, including possibilities that directly link the raw/analyzed data with lab notebook entries. Many ELNs are very specific for a discipline (e.g., synthetic chemistry, molecular biology). Given the increasing interdisciplinarity, a good ELN should allow entries from different experimental setups (e.g., synthetic chemistry & microbiology). Also, a central platform for data backup, which also allows storage of large files and multiple data (large storage space) and that is serviced, should be provided at the department or university.

column131: A helpful electronic lab notebook is missing. A system focussing solely on a graphic user interface is not helpful because user defined scripts and employing linux terminal commands is often much faster than employing a GUI. A concept most be developed which can handle both worlds (data prepared by a GUI or by a terminal script) and does not result in additional workload. The ELN must allow to process data from most codes from static quantum chemisty (e.g. ORCA), molecular dynamics (e.g. LAMMPS), solid state programs (e.g. VASP) and ab initio molecular dynamics codes (e.g. CP2K), just to name few examples. I think only an open source project can handle this.
